Author: lotso125
Content:
NFL Scorigami: taking scorekeeping to another level.

So.... I stumbled upon this thing when I was researching about how much different variation you can get from every NFL game, and this happened because NFL have a different points depending on how you score on the game. For those of you that didn't know, there are different points that u can get in a game, such as 6 point for touchdown, 3 for field goal/kicking, and 1 point for successful kick after a touchdown. From various combinations, we can deduct on how popular certain score is, and which score is not as popular.

Scorigami itself  is a concept thought up by American Journalist and Humorist Jon Bois. It is the art of building final scores that have never happened before in NFL history. Due to the unique nature of how points are scored in American Football, where it is impossible to score 1 point on its own, as well as the rarity of the 2 point safety and 8 point touchdown and 2 point conversion, there are a lot of scores that are possible, but have never happened.

After I know all about scorigami, I started to check the website, reddit thread, and social medias regarding is there any updates toward the scorigami. I remember the last updates to the scorigami is on November 16, 2025 when the Buffalo Bills win against Tampa Bay Buccaneers with the score of 44 - 32.  When I saw the recent update to the scorigami, I feel... hyped(?) for no reason. I feel like scorigami in a way is just another type of collectibles, since you can never guess and predict the outcome of the game. There are more "common" scores like 20 - 17, which occurred like 298 times and 27 - 24 that occurred 240 times, but yeah there are also some "rarer" scores and unique/SSR games that only happened once in a lifetime (for now) that just add more layer to scorigami itself. All and all, I like scorigami, collecting things are cool, and NFL please ban tush push ‚ù§Ô∏è

Author: lotso125
Content:
I've done my research, and i present you: the most european non-european countries.

basically, it's a list of countries that not particularly  a part of or a member of european union, but they're participating in a lot of things that ties to european politics and cultures (yes it's pointless but bear with me pls). some of the reason why these countries are participating in european thingy is because they want to join some better league, or the big boy league bcs they feel like they could be profited or compete on a higher level. institutions like Council of Europe (CoE) is open for countries outside of EU as long as they're following EU's protocol about various things such as human rights and contributions to the institutions. they could be an observer countries or actively helping to the cause of CoE itself. 

other things like the UEFA Champions League (UCL) and Eurobasket also open for countries that want to join, and thats why countries like Israel and teams like Fenerbache can compete to win UEFA trophies. a lot of times they join UEFA or European Sport League because they feel like "too good" in their own region and/or rejected from the said region. all and all, a lot of these countries are trying to fight because these trophies seems to be more "prestige" and cool (?) by default.

Without further ado, this is the list of those said countries. lemme know if there are any wrong input or things that could be added. thankyou!

Author: lotso125
Content:
dad shoes are great not because they're comfortable, but also because their silhouettes are sick af. lemme explain.

so for a couple of months now, i've been obsessed with chunky shoes or "dad" shoes. i personally think that they always looks cool in a flawless, effortless way. i do also find how easy it is to mix and match dad shoes to my usual outfits. even though a lot of people also points out things like "Y2K aesthetics" and "boomer vibes" with the shoes, me personally looks at it in a nostalgic way, how a lot of older streetwear and brands used to create a lot of shoes with this type of silhouettes as well. it keep reminds me of the day where yeezy drops are a hype and a moment of itself, and also the core foundation of skateboarding culture as well, since a lot of skateboard shoes are also chunky.

but i do have some ick about those chunky shoes, especially when they're overdoing it. what i mean is silhouettes that just didn't make any sense and just ugly to begin with. i'm talking about FILA Disruptors, Converse Run Star Motion, UGGs, and those pink Crocs Clogs. wdym they deserve a spot in a chunky shoes tier? in the world where Yeezy 700 and NB 990 exist, i don't think that they belong in the same "genes". i do agree that those shoes are chunky af and also gives u some height, but chunky shoes is not always about that. chunky shoes (despite being called ugly shoes) is a culture of its own, have their old-school silhouettes, and also need to give you those "nostalgic" feelings when ur wearing it, so if your favorite shoes are listed before, sorry to say that they're not a chunky/ dad shoes in my book.

all and all, i'll say that dad shoes are great, not every chunky shoes can be categorized into dad shoes, and i hate and love you kardashians to popularized this style of shoe ‚ù§Ô∏è .

my top 5 of dad shoes (rn):
- Adidas Ozweego
- Nike Vomero
- Asics Gel Kayano 14 (and jjjjound collab!)
- Yeezy 700 & 500
- NB 1906R, 2002R, and 530 (hehe i can't choose)

Author: lotso125
Content:
because of me getting bedrest for some days, i realized that i missed some of lego's older, own franchises.

i collect various types of legos since i was a little kid, and i remember those days where lego have their own franchises that is unique and also very cool to see, such as Bionicles, Hero Factories, Power Miner, and Mars Missions. these days, the only lego's franchise that still kinda survived is the ninjago franchise which, isn't that bad in my opinion, but probably bcs it's not there when i was a little, i have little to no interest for that specific franchise. these days if we're talking about legos, we all can agree that its getting more realistic as they taken more realistic license like the monalisa, fender (the guitar brand), and nintendo. those collab isn't bad at all, but sometimes i just missed my old franchises y'know? those janky-wasteland robot look that bionicle, or the mecha/zoid look of the hero factories is also very eye-catching for me, even till this day. 

basically, the short reason why lego are discontinuing those franchises is because the re-launch for it are flopped. the other reason why is because lego didn't want to make another mold for their parts. since legos are made from plastic and molded with a machine, every piece have their own unique mold. if they want to create another "unique" molds like what they do to bionicle parts like their head, torso and feets, they need to spend more money just to create a unique mold for (almost) every part, and its not good economically. lego also share that they always trying to put existing mold/shape into sets and trying to be as unique as possible. thats why u can found sausage shape in titanic set, frog in sakura tree set, and lego hat in cactus set. lego also trying to commit to long term sustainability project starting in 2024, by choosing more sustainable materials, use recyclable packaging, and reduce greenhouse emission.

Author: lotso125
Content: all and all, thats why the old franchises is not gonna be back sooner or later. i do hope that one day there'll be some way to "revive" the old sets, but for now, im gonna collect my money to buy the nissan skyline or the S2K set *sigh*

Author: lotso125
Content:
Adidas NMD is the start of sneaker craze for my generation, and it was cool for that moment. i remember back in 2015 when adidas put us in a chokehold when they dropped both Adidas NMD in the original red and blue, and also dropping the triple white ultra boost. the resell price of NMD itself is also wild, since i remember this dude on Instagram bought the shoe from a reseller for 1000 USD, bcs it was THAT hype. after the initial hype itself, adidas also dropped more color for the NMD, but the OG still the one sticks in my memory like a sore thumb. it was that good at that time. one thing that adidas failed to foresee about the NMD craze is that:

1. the hype was there, but the second drop for the OG colorway takes too long and ppl already moving on to another trend
2. adidas didn't create "scarcity" for the drop, making sure that everyone can get a pair and didn't qualify it as a "grail" on their second drop.
3. other brand (specifically air jordan) already crowned as the goat shoe brand at that time, and adidas couldn't compete with that.

Adidas eventually drop the second silhouette for NMD with the OG color and everything, but it was too late (and the silhouette is ugly too imho). sneakers already becoming a bigger market and Nike is leading far and beyond with other hits like Air Jordan 11 "Space Jam" or even Nike Kobe 6 "The Grinch". All and All, rest in peace NMD. you were the hype shoes fore father in my generation.

Author: lotso125
Content:
Louis Vuitton X Takashi Murakami (TakashiPom) is not something new, but its the epitome of Japanese custom culture at the highest level. back in 2002, Marc Jacobs invite Murakami to custom Louis Vuitton classic monogram collection. this collab blows up and made Murakami the first person to rework the house's emblem and put the collab at the immediate place on both fashion and art history book. this collab is not a safe custom either. Murakami put his signature characters and color popped palette that immediately become pop-cultural status symbols. we can see celebrities like paris hilton and pharell williams waring this article and the collab itself even made its way to movies like mean girls. this collab so popular that it stays in the store for 12 years and the resale price continue to climb through the roof.

nowadays, LV doing their 3rd collabs with Murakami, with Zendaya as its ambassador. LV x murakami shows the uniqueness once again with the cherries, cherry blossom, and the iconic monogram superflat panda to welcome the season. this collab isn't only important because of the culture, but also because its signalling full-circle fashion moment that people don't wanna miss out on. if the first collab was, in Marc Jacobs words, a monumental marriage between art and business, this latest collab is aiming for global domination.

Author: lotso125
Content:
the younger generation are trading their nike tech for quarter zip. is it a vibe shift, maturing moment, or whitepassing?

in 2025, we've seen all sort of trends in fashion and quarter zip is probably just one of them. but this trend, and the memes revolving the trend itself.... is amazing. i saw how those so-called "young gentleman" swapping their look that usually consist of shiesty, nike techs and black air force to quarter zip, khakis, and dress shoes. the color pick is also drastically different as well. nike tech are popular for their fierce and bold colors like red, navy, and aqua blue, while this same people are choosing burgundy, nude, and ash for their quarter zip. after the wardrobe change, they also tend to fix their behaviors and habit for some reason. its either because they fw the change, or simply just "looking the part" and being performative about the shift in fashion trend itself. you can see them bringing books, glass of matcha, and also goyard duffle bag (or just duffle bag lol) as accessories of their fashion statement. not only people on social media, this trend is also actually making a movement that celebrities lean to join as well. for example, we can see central cee also rocking the quarter zip trend, even though he was one of the people that popularize nike tech back in 2024. so what happened? why..... why does is work?

i will say, the earliest time i saw the quarter zip trend on tiktok is probably around a month ago or so, where this young tiktoker rocking the zip with matcha on his hand. in the same video, he explain how he's "elevated", "upgraded",  and "matured" with the outfit that he choose. this isn't a rare occurrence tbh, since we've seen something like this before, where people are trying to be seen as an adult and trying to remove their "younger" and "reckless" looks. for example, we've seen how Jay-Z on his song titled "30 something" talking about how he's maturing and forever

Author: lotso125
Content:
swapping his baggy outfits to tuxedo that we know today. its the little thing that matters, and yes, some people will undergo those type of drastic changes in their lives. no shame for anyone that actually trade their "kidult" outfit for a proper one bcs to be fair, we've been there. it's a bit insulting in a way, but life goes on and as a male, there's this area where realization hits u and u need to make an executive decision about your change of wardrobe, and it ok.

other than an attempt to be more mature in some way, a lot of people, especially black people, see this trend as white passing. they kinda see this quarter zip trend as an attempt to "weaken" black  presence and to make black people blend in the white-dominated world (their words not mine). if im being honest here, there's no issue about elevating yourself or simply wearing some sort of clothes in your life. it's not always about trying to "fit in", even though almost EVERY fashion trend is all about fitting into some mold of the society. the main outtakes of the quarter zip trend is that, these young gentlemen are trying to look better, to finally growing out of their old self, and reinventing themself to become some sort of this, kid in adult spaces. you're allowed to wear something a bit more "serious" and "preppy", and if the trend doesn't suit you, thats fine too. quarter zip isn't a device to turn people white anyway, its just a piece of clothing at the end of the day.

all and all, this trend is one hell of a ride that really fill my november FYP (till today sih), and i support the quarter zip movement if you're actually looking for "that" piece of clothing that could elevate your style to the next level. not for me tho i still enjoy my sneakers and baggy pants trend hehe.

PS: nike also doing the quarter zip now,so if u still find it hard to try another brand, just go to ur nearest nike store lmao.

Author: lotso125
Content:
So, i created this spreadsheet just because theres a lot of people out there that keeps on asking questions like "does it called JKT48 bcs they have 48 member? what 48 means???". i'll answer this for you in this discussion.

first of all, 48 in JKT48 signifies the ties with their sister group, which is AKB48. 48 in AKB48 itself means the location of the AKB48 theater in japan, which is at Akihabara (in short, AKB), the 4th building, on 8th floor. tadaaaa, AKB48 everyone!!

second of all, i think at some point JKT48 do have 48 members, but the numbers keeps being added and reduced because new generation of member is getting added almost every year and members also graduated from the group (which could be another discussion one day). so yeah.... the answer is yes and no about the amount of members in the group. if you wanna know how many member does JKT48 have, just look at the table that i created (yes i counted manually) (yes this data is like 10+ years old) (yes i still update this thing from time to time). enjoy! 

*data per December 4th, 2025

Author: lotso125
Content:
Hashire, penguin! Suica retires its penguin mascot.

Japan is a country full of mascot that we all love and adore. Peko-chan, Kumamon, Pikachu, and Glico-man is just to name a few of them. a lot of those mascots are surviving through the years and decades of iconic logos and packaging. but earlier on november, East Japan Railway (JR East) said to retire the suica penguin, or the mascot of their contactless card payment that mainly used at train platforms. the company itself said on social media that the mascot is "graduating", which receiving the same treatment as some "idol" in japan.

the change itself isn't because of the penguin's "lack of popularity" or anything. the company said that they're restructuring itself to shift JR East from an old-school firm dependent on train revenue to a fintech-focused company. the company aims to change the transit card into modern mobile payment platform, a super-app offering peer-to-peer transactions and a banking back-end, along with futuristic tech that will eliminate the need for station turnstiles. they're doing this not only to "reinvent" themself, but to compete with other payment method like paypay that use QR payment system that's more flexible and quick. suica on the other hand seems to be inferior, especially because what they can use are limited to trains and vending machines, while other fintech apps can also provide even larger method of payment that could be used almost everywhere, which JR east want to compete.

all and all, i can see why JR east want to make this change, since the use of QR is already very large and common in japan. as a financial company, of course it's a good step forward a newer type of technology, eventho they need to retire the penguin. I do personally hope that the bronze statue at shinjuku isn't gonna be stripped down soon tho üôÇ

Author: lotso125
Content:
i rarely watch anime, but this one anime really captivate me and i honestly think that this is my top 3 best anime i've ever watch, ever. the title of the said anime is "sakurasou no pet na kanojo". it was adapted from a light novel with the same title. the main story of the anime itself is about this main protagonist called Kanda Sorata that forced to live in sakura dormitory that notoriously  full of "troublemakers" because he keep a stray cat in his previous dorm room. As he starts to get used to the life in the dorm, Mashiro Shiina, a world-famous artist who cannot even take care of her daily life, moves in. Sorata is forced to become Mashiro's caretaker (hence the "pet" in the title of the anime). eventho it was called the dormitory of troublemaker, i'll say is just full of misfits that didn't really fit with the society, which really, not a bunch of bad person in a way. this anime focusing on the story between kanda and mashiro, but also involving other member of the dormitories as well, which really enrich the slice of life aspect of the anime.

what i really love about this anime, is that eventho they're focusing on the story of the 2 protagonists, we still see the connection between 3 other tenant of the dorm, which in a way, really tells you about human connection. i will say, out of 5 people in the dorm, there are 2 main character, but no NPC's. all of them got a fair share of backstories and dialogues, which hits closer to me more than anything. i can see that the anime adaptation really care about creating the world where all 5 of them are equally important, and no stories are untold. when i was finishing the anime, i felt, happy tbh. happy because everyone told their stories, because everyone stories and issues got resolved (kinda), and because this is the type of anime that actually care so much despite the lack of episodes.

Author: lotso125
Content:
the last thing that makes me enjoy watching this anime is also bcs their stories are interconnected in a very good way, which i enjoy with all of the pacing. the fact that they could compile everything within 24 episodes really makes it special for me. i wasn't a fan of long anime, especially those type of anime that have multiple seasons and arcs (yea im looking at you, one piece). 24 episodes are good enough to encapsulate all the feels, emotions, and drama within the anime, which is great.

all and all, i'm aware that sakurasou no pet na kanojo is probably not one of the "best" anime in unison, or according to the majority of people, but this particular anime is special for me, and i will say, yeah, this anime is on my top 3 best anime in my opinion, so take it or leave it i guess lol.

PS: the 1st opening for the anime is great, and i recommend y'all to listen to it hehe

Author: lotso125
Content:
your favorite piece of clothing might be designed for conflicts. take an example of bomber jacket, trench coat, flared pants or chinos. those articles were made not necessarily because of modes and trends, but sometimes out of necessities. Trench coats were a lightweight solution for wet trenches back in WW1, and bomber jackets were designed for warmth and mobility for the first fighter pilots. hell, even T-shirts were used to be use as navy undergarments.

but when the war ends, these piece of clothing need to go somewhere, somewhere with a different meaning. for example, take a look at flared pants. this pants were initially used by the navy through WW2, and the wide bottom were designed to be easy to roll up when there was water on board. the same pants was used 20 years later by students and hippies protesting Vietnam wars, with the big difference was called bellbottom pants. other example was combat boots used by the UK punk movements and French beret used by black panther movement as well. those garments doesn't lose its political meanings, but their positions in political compass surely shifted.

nowadays, a lot of these fashion items that used to have political meanings surely lost its meaning completely. cargo pants now is the cornerstone of almost every fashion look but notably for Y2K, trench coat become the staple of French romance movies, and raf simons camo bomber jacket would become a fashion grail priced at 50K or something. all and all, i will say that fashion do change in purposes, whether it was political or not, war or peace, it was something for function, and you sell it for meanings, and people buy it without understand the means and just see it as a drip, or a piece of clothing, which was intended all along.

Author: lotso125
Content:
Visvim, the future vintage.

since american military base was placed in okinawa in 1945, the wave of american culture and heritage hits japan like a wave. a lot of younger generation of japanese was captivated by its culture like outfit, lifestyle, and cuisine, marking the new trend of "americana" culture in japan. one of the teenagers back then that got influenced by the americana wave was a young hiroki nakamura, which later become the creator of visvim, which ill cover more in this thread. nakamura later move to alaska, which later gives him some time exploring rural america and growing his love for snowboarding that land him his most important gig, which is a design job for japanese division of burton snowboarding company. this gig also revived his obsession towards american clothing and footwear, particularly work boots and moccasins. with that obsession, nakamura later decided to create his own label, named visvim.

what i love with visvim is that it's different from other japanese americana label. while many japanese labels draw inspiration from ivy and american workwear, visvim abandoned that and delved deep into ancient folk customs. i mean, nakamura's first work of visvim was a sneaker that fused native american moccasins with hi-tech sneakers technologies. even after that, nakamura still fuse a lot of cultural design and inspirations while designing visvim drops. heavy wool coats from tibet, hand-dyed blankets from navajo reservations and colourful folk art from Guatemala is only a few of the inspirations behind his design, which is very cool to me. other reason why i love this brand is because of his future vintage idea.

Author: lotso125
Content:
in his GQ interview, nakamura said that "i want to create things that can be vintage in the future. That‚Äôs my goal: future vintage." the way that he creates visvim and then his ideation behind every piece was... amazing for me. imagine a person trying to create something that not only cool for today, but also a vintage piece for tommorow. truly a crazy idea for me. i guess thats what happen when you combine things that u love and passionate about to create a fashion line that really unique.

all and all, i will say that visvim is great, and the least greatest thing about it is the price. so yeah...... i need that moccasin for cheaper pls thx nakamura-san üôè

Author: lotso125
Content:
this is so random, but i was picking out some wine (for some reason) and i was faced with options of the 4 pinots, which it blanc, noir, gris, and meunier. so... whats the difference?

basically, all 4 types is just a varieties of pinot grapes, which have distinct characteristics. pinot grape itself originated from burgundy, france, and the name pinot translated into "pine", describing the cone-like shape of the grape bunches. ok so back to the 4 pinots ok sorry

- blanc is a white grape and produces dry wines with good acidity and aromas of white fruit, citrus and flowers. Its mainly grown in italy, germany and austria and is often used in the production of sparkling and semi-sparkling wines.

- noir is a red grape variety and produces medium to light-bodied wines with aromas of red fruits, spices and earth. It is grown mainly in france, germany, and specifically california and is often used in the production of champagne and sparkling wines, as well as the great red wines of Burgundy.

- gris is a white grape variety that produces dry, light and fresh wines with aromas of white fruit, citrus and flowers. It originated in Italy and is now cultivated all over the world, especially in germany and france.

- meunier is a red grape that is often used in the production of champagne and sparkling wines. It produces smooth, fruity and aromatic wines with red fruit and spice aromas. It is mainly cultivated in france, but also in belgium and germany.

so yeah... basically, noir and meunier are red grapes, while blanc and gris are white grapes. noir and meunier are often used in the production of champagne, sparkling and large red wines, while blanc and gris are used in the production of dry and sparkling wines (there u go) (i'm not good at explaining wine i only know how to drink sorry)

all and all, those are the 4 type of pinot that i know, and i bought riesling instead of either of the pinots hehe. lemme know if u want me to talk more abt wine or spirits in general!

Author: lotso125
Content:
if you're new at liquor, there must be a lot of question regarding the name of some liquor. sometimes, the same liquor or close enough liquor could also be named differently. but why is that happened, and what's the difference between them? ill explain what i know about this (which isn't a lot).

tequila and mezcal: technically, all tequila is mezcal. mezcal refers to spirits made from the agave plant, while tequila refers to a specific type of mezcal that can only be made from blue Weber agave in five Mexican states

whisky and whiskey: generally comes from the place of origin. as a rule of thumb, whiskey mostly was made in both ireland and usa, while whisky was everywhere from scotland to australia.

champagne. it's only called champagne if the sparkling wine was made in the region of champagne, france. even if made with the same ingredients, anything made outside of champagne can't be called one (thats why cremant exist lol). other name for sparkling wines are prosecco (italy), cava (spain), and sekt (germany and austria)

cognac. every cognac is brandy, but not every brandy is cognac, since cognac can only be produced in cognac region in france. other brandy's also produced with a location-specific name such as jerez (spain), pisco (peru), and slivovitz (balkan region)

fortified wines. port (portugal), sherry (spain), marsala (sicily) and madeira (also portugal) is all fortified wine that commonly mixed with brandy or other spirits.

pinga or cachaca. brazilian liquor that a bit similar to rum. both were made from sugarcane, but rum traditionally was made with molasses instead of raw sugarcane.

i guess that's all i know.... yeah again another unimportant knowledge but yknow.... it is what it is lol. lemme know if i missed anything in this list!

Author: lotso125
Content:
one time i was hanging out on this autoshop-themed cafe in bandung, and they got break fluids in their chiller, which later they told me that it was apple and gum flavored drinks. without thinking twice, i bought the drink bcs their packaging is cool. that drink got me thinking, "chaos packaging do be very effective lmao". but what is "chaos packaging"?

so basically, chaos packaging takes familiar products and reimagines their containers in unconventional ways, as we can see at moschino's windex bottle perfume, departed spirit's motor oil vodka, and maison margiela vacuum sealed tshirt. more than a novelty, chaos packaging disrupts the predictable, engaging consumers with designs that evoke curiosity, nostalgia, or humor. i mean, who could predict an unsuspecting windex bottle in your vanity happen to be a perfume, right? me personally, i love chaos packaging. not only because of how silly and unique it is, but also how marketable and shelf appealing it is. like, imagine the story and narrative that you can build about and around the product, and also the social media campaign that you can do to suit the theme of the product, or the packaging itself. i'll say, your product could be mid at best, but a good packaging could elevate the sales even more in my opinion, so now imagine if you have a good product and an iconic packaging to accompany it. it could be legendary tbh.

but to pick what chaos packaging suit your product, i guess it all comes down to the story, practicality and the packaging itself. for stories, u need to know all ideation and concept behind the product and the packaging, why it was shaped like that, or the ads regarding the product itself. for the practicality, is really self-explanatory. the product need to be easy to dispense, enjoy and use. if your chaos packaging didn't allow that, then its a bad packaging after all. and the last thing is the shape of the packaging itself. weird is ok, but i guess some norm need to be used. thats all lmao.

Author: lotso125
Content:
since i've been talking abt liquor for a couple days now, i might share one of the better whisky that i've ever tasted, which is an islay whisky called lagavulin. before i explain the taste, i think i'll explain what islay whisky is

so basically islay whisky is a single malt whisky that was made in islay, located at the west of scotland. some says that the irish monks come to the islay in the early 1300. those distilleries also started as farm distilleries in the 1700, retreated to the caves in the islay to avoid alcohol tax, which could be counted as illegal distillery back in the day. a lot of those distillery also located on the coast of islay, to easily "smuggle" the whisky. those reason is also why a lot of islay whisky have a hint of seaweed and sea, notably because of the type of water that was used. their wheat and barley also have a heavy, smoky aroma which usually be described as "medicinal flavor" by whisky enthusiast. this really differentiate the whisky that was made on the mainland because they have a lighter flavor thanks to the usage of spring water.

now we're talking about lagavulin. lagavulin is both the name of the product and distillery, which produce different whisky ages from 8 years to 30ish years iirc. my usual go to (if the bars have them) is the 16 years old lagavulin. i remember it was 2023, and the batch of that year tasted amazing. i can taste the smokiness and how peat-y the whisky was, and like what islay whisky usually is, have a whiff of the sea (which is very faint and i can only smell it after i finished the glass). overall, it tasted sweet, a bit nutty and vanilla-y, with a fruity, orange aftertaste. i will say, for quite the price back then, it was an experience.

all and all, a lot of these distillery usually create a batch every year, and each year could taste a bit differently, which really added to the overall experience imho. the 2023 batch was good, and im looking forward to try more in the future hehe.

Author: lotso125
Content:
so i was reading and searching about glasses, and while searching for one, i saw this brand called Jacques Marie Mage. i was bewildred by the price tags, and how exclusive it is. i also saw someone said that jacques marie mage (JMM) is the "birkin of sunglasses". so it got me looking deeper at this brand. how tf this micro designer brand produce such lavish products?

JMM was made by jerome mage, a French designer who founded the brand in Los Angeles in 2014. he basically create sunglasses and optics in general, usually made of acetate and other material like titanium and other precious metals. his "mark" of brand in his glasses are an arrowhead at the temple, a nod to americana style that infatuated jacques. One of the unique features of JMM frames though is the individual numbering and once-run nature of their releases. Once a specific frame and colorway is done, its not bound to be repeated again. their most famous silhouette is probably the Dealan, which was inspired by bob dylan and also, one of my favorite article from the brand. the shape of the article is timeless, and classy in my opinion, which i adore very much. other article that i also like is the enzo and molino as well. but yknow, the shape of their glasses are pretty unique in general.

other than the hefty price and the material used in the making, their presentation of the product is also very exquisite. the use of beautiful silk presentation box is on par with what you‚Äôd get from a watchmaker like rolex, and includes a wonderful Italian-leather sleeve and cleaning cloth, plus myriad story details about your frame. it‚Äôs really unlike anything you‚Äôve seen in optics, and also differentiate itself from a lot of high end brands like wayfarer and tom ford.

all and all, JMM is actually a good option if ur looking for a luxury glasses brand that offer uniqueness in every articles and also have value in the craftmanship itself. i mean its a valid glasses but the price is... still better than tom ford lol

Author: lotso125
Content:
if you follow Timoth√©e Chalamet on Instagram, i'm sure that ur aware with him promoting his up and coming movie called Marty Supreme. you will also realize that he's campaigning his movie while wearing the signature Marty Supreme jacket with bold blue and orange color, and also those table tennis balls with stars on them. so what's up with the jacket and the movie promotions?

so basically, marty supreme is a sport-comedy movie inspired by american table tennis player, Marty Reisman. this movie already premiered at 2025 New York Film Festival on 6 October 2025, but set on released by A24 on 25 December 2025. all i know about the premise of the movie itself is that this is a ping-pong drama set in 1950s new york city where Marty goes to hell and back in pursuit of greatness. while promoting the movie, we saw how Timoth√©e Chalamet wearing his in character costume, where he's rocking the buzz cut, wearing a frameless glasses, and also the Marty Supreme tracksuit, which is the main point of this discussion.

the tracksuit itself was designed by Doni Nahmias, the founder and designer of the luxury brand Nahmias. he was basically collaborating this capsule with Chalamet, Taylor McNeill (Chalamet's stylist), and A24. this drop was crazy, since Chalamet only post the drop on his insta with the store address and captioned "C U at 7", and people already lining up as early as 4:30. GQ calling this capsule "The signature garment of 2025 that's not even from YSL or Miu Miu, but relatively affordable, albeit extremely scarce". Nahmias himself also reportedly said "this is crazy" several times during the drop. the $250 tracksuit was sold out at the end of the day and some people already selling the drop for $4.000 on Grailed. today, the same tracksuit (the blue colorway) was selling for $1.797 on StockX, which solidifies their status as a new cultural status symbol. personally i love this jacket. this capsule reminds me of those 2015 thrift jacket era where people deliberately

Author: lotso125
Content:
thrifted those light, parachute jacket with popping colors and 90's design, which i didn't buy bcs i thought it was "meh" lol. but yeah, those boxy, oversized fit with "Marty Supreme" logo and 3 stars apparently was enough to create another hype drop in 2025.

i will say the marketing made by Chalamet is crazy good, and people was hooked, line and sinker with this "movie merch" eventho the film itself hasn't hit the theater. I've seen various meme fashion page where they said that the 2026 NYC male on soho gonna be people wearing those Marty Supreme fits while rocking matching orange arc'teryx beanie, drinking natty light, and ordering small plates on wine bars. I also remember how they're flying out the Marty Supreme orange blimp all across South California, Chalamet videos where he said that he's proposing the idea of painting the Statue of Liberty orange and Chalamet posting picture of celebrities like Tom Brady, Kylie Jenner, and Bill nye wearing the Marty Supreme Threads. it was amazing how he was "all in" with this promotion (probably because he's the co-producer but idk) and how invested people with this marketing. about the marketing itself, Nahmias also involved with the making of the lookbook. he even said that going "rogue" was the main idea of the promotion, and he's focusing on showing "greatness" through vintage sportswear and GOATs of sports.

all and all, Nahmias also said that there are tons of colorways for the tracksuit, so hopefully people can cop the rarer silhouette like pink and baby blue. my take on this discussion is that they need to create more merch tour so that it could be accessible to a wider audience, and Chalamet, i know that i didn't know u personally, but i love how you could bag a LA baddie, make her support the NY Knicks, create a huge buzz all around your upcoming movies, and also tap in to WWE cultures. you're really is, the Lisan al-Ghaib.

Author: lotso125
Content:
this is probably my favorite hoodie of all time (for now), and i bought it from a small store in the heart of Paris, France. the brand and store is called Blue Garage Paris, and they're located at 5 Rue du March√© des Blancs Manteaux, which is really close to the garden of national archives. the store itself is pretty small, and the signboard is also pretty hidden for some reason (really bad for business tbh) but i was strolling around and saw the word "LOCATED IN PARIS" on the window and i was intrigued, so i enter the establishments.

inside, i was surprised to know that it was a clothing store (bcs i have no idea before) and immediately i saw a lot of hoodies and shirt (and also try on some) before actually choose to buy the hoodie. the hoodie design was.... minimalistic imho. i pick the item that was supposedly made for their Tokyo collection, which is why they have a big dragon graphic on the back. the hoodie itself was very comfortable and thick. i guess it was suppose to be a winter hoodie, but i do still wear it in Jakarta lol. i feel like, this particular hoodie was shaped really well, and it do fits properly for me. all i know is that this isn't something i can lend to my (future) gf if she was feeling cold lmao

but after i bought one of their hoodie, i want to search this brand, which at the end i didn't really find anything. on their website, they only tell u that "As a crew who originated in Paris, we proudly wear our 'Located in Paris' identity and share our lifestyle and culture through quality products. Our graphics are inspired by our travels to New York City, Tokyo and Los Angeles, where we set up pop-up stores, collaborations and wholesales with local artists and entities.", which is really something. no designer name, no owner, no nothing. i feel like i just bought a secret street wear from France or something lol. but all i know about this brand is that their hoodie is good, i like the design, and please don't steal mine lol.

Author: lotso125
Content:
i wasn't aware of this discussion before, but after i saw a lot of instances where it happened, i kinda understand why people are losing their mind about this. today, i'll talk about "Swag Gaps"

so basically, swag gaps is when a couple has a different "swag" or preference of clothing and fashion. it could also means that one of them might be less fashionable, or appear not to make as much of an effort with how they look. one of the most prominent example of swag gaps is Justin and Hailey Bieber, where we can see how Justin was usually can be seen wearing hoodies and crocs, while Hailey is usually wearing more "refined" outfits. debates about swag gaps sparks in social medias like TikTok and Instagram, left people actually in the middle whether different swag or efforts are really a big of a deal, or if both parties need to make an effort in their fashion game. some people even go so far as making it a "dealbreaker" if their partner actually have different swag or just wearing "plain" clothes.

i think having different style is okay. think of it as "the nerd bagging the cheerleader" type of thing. i only said this bcs i'm in no position to call anyone fashion as mid. i always the type to let u know that u gotta wear anything comfortable for you, without the need to seek validation or riding the trend lol. if its good, comfy, and practical for u, then rock that shit. u don't need anyone to tell u that it isn't swaggy or anything, as long as ur comfortable in ur own skin. other thing i wanna highlight is that the composition of drip or swag itself. if you know the "rick owens outfit" meme and the "i wore vintage issey miyake while she wore $5 dress from shein" meme, you know what i mean. drip couldn't be counted from the tag, the price, the brand, or anything else. you make the drip. you make yourself comfortable. you make yourself seen because you define what you wear, and NEVER the other way around.

so yeah... more discussion about swag gaps just lemme know ok?

Author: lotso125
Content:
i love cocktails, and i do enjoy a lot of different books talking about cocktails as well. what i like from cocktails is how they could both enhance or destroy the flavor of the drink, how intricate some cocktail is (I'm looking at you, gimlet, Singapore sling, and tom and jerry), and also how cocktail can be both medicine and poison. bars in Indonesia do create the popular cocktails like negroni and martini, but a lot of times they also create their own version of cocktails (which we usually call "pletokan"). sometimes, they mix pills and medicine into the cocktail, just for the sake of getting drunk. i will say, i love cocktails, but i do need the medicine side of the drink. i will say, cocktail could be very therapeutic for me, because it "healed" me in a lot of ways. some of my friends called me an alcoholic for trying so many type of cocktails, but i just can't helped it lol. i love almost every type of em.

but back to the literature. i read a lot of books that makes me realize that every cocktails are great, because a lot of them could be made out of different liquor, different technique, and also different "finesse". if u told me back in 2015 that different amount of stirs and duration of shake could affect the taste and consistency of cocktails, i actually will laugh at you, because the younger me would never comprehend such ridiculous and trivial things like that, but apparently those things do affect those factors lol. even bartending also have different styles. you have your typical, poised, old school bartender, flashy, captivating flair bartender, or avant-garde molecular mixologist. but you know what they said, different types means different opportunities to try them all.

all and all, i will say that i do enjoy cocktails and whisk(e)ys. and for some recommendations if you want to read more about cocktails and bartending, i suggest you to read Jerry Thomas' bartender guide, bartender (manga), and to have and have another by philip greene. enjoy!

Author: lotso125
Content:
in the big 2025, i don't think anyone didn't know what chrome hearts is. they have a unique design and style that really pop off your outfits everytime someone is wearing one. from rings to bracelets, chrome hearts is probably still one of the hottest jewelry brands out there. but the biggest criticism towards the brand is always the exclusivity and price, which really creates unnecessary demands for the product. their crazy resell price also create a big shift in the market, which people nowadays was looking for a replacement brand or something that's pretty similar to the brand itself. brands like HARDIHOODER, A&G, OHTNYC, and LIONHEART are infamous for having a similar style with chrome hearts, which all inspired from french christian gothic style. but the main question is, what is french christian gothic?

basically, this style of aesthetic originated from the 12th-16th centuries in europe, where the architectural design popularize the sharp, pointy, intricate details. this trend influence the style of the jewelry with the intricate design, dramatic color contrast, and symbolic motifs that often used to represent love, god and eternity. a lot of gothic jewelry also worn by the wealthy and clergy, used in religious context as a symbol of faith and power. thats why back then, a lot of people were using gothic crosses for praying purposes as well. but in the 20th century, we also see the rise of gothic subculture, where the jewelry are used as a form of self-expressions. the dark and mysterious image of the jewelry becoming the cornerstone of that era, where they change the way they see the jewelry to something that portray death, romanticism, and supernatural. punk and metal also heavily influenced by the gothic jewelry, where we can see bands and musicians like

Author: lotso125
Content:
guns & roses or aerosmith rocking the sterling metal goth jewelry itself. i've been talking about how statements and interest towards fashions are always been changing from time to time, and french gothic jewelry also had the same situations. the way that something so close to religion and clergy now turned into a daily fashion and grail. both are worshipped, but for two different reason.

all and all, i think gothic jewelry is always great, since people are always trying to combine something really close to their heart (like religion and love) but with more drip and style. gothic jewelry kinda nailed it, and i guess the era of gothic jewelry will never pass and people are still gonna wear it one way or another. me personally? i don't own any of those chrome hearts but maybe in 2026 üëÄ

Author: lotso125
Content:
lately, i felt "bored" with streetwear brands, because i feel like, sometimes they're just recycling old ideas and/or being uncreative with their release. i was like, browsing thru GRAILED and will find nothing really popping out, especially towards the newer brands. it feels almost repetitive tbh. but it was changed when i found this brand called Happy Memories Don't Die (HMDD).

basically, HMDD is a brand based in LA. this brand was started by brothers Jack and Jyde Manson back in 2019, but according to them, they only really started to get serious on this brand in 2023. looking at the brand, i guess they're inspired from other brands like adidas, denim tears, and evisu, which u can really see the inspirations in some of their articles. what i love about this brand is a lot of things, but to start it, is the way they design their drops. i feel like, sometimes streetwear can be too much and/or trying too hard to create something that looks "hard" and "tuff", which ultimately failed and just looking like an eyesore tbh. with HMDD, they keep it simple, but with a good executions. their jorts? good. their sweatpants? good. their shirts and hoodies? also good. even their dirt bike inspired shirt and jackets are flawlessly good without incorporating way too much design and brandings.

next thing that i like is how they love to play with proportions. they have boxy hoodie, a slightly baggy sweatpants, oversized hoodie, and also fitted shirt that just shows the range of the fits that they offer. and the last thing is that how they're not afraid to use various colors on their pieces. from blood orange hoodie to white and purple sweatpants, they really got it. sometimes, black, grey , white, and other monochrome colors feels a tad too "safe" yknow? but HMDD really understand how to combine those colors without making it too much.

i guess that's all for now lol, and here are some of my favorite articles from HMDD. lemme know if u want me to talk about other brands ok?

Author: lotso125
Content:
since i've been talking about chrome hearts (CH) before, i think their influences are really big in east asia rather than in america. when americans are just really tap into the brand by seeing and following their favorite rappers and influencers, CH in countries like south korea and japan is already huge and have their own cult followers. musicians like bigbang and 2NE1 also wearing those brands and others before it was cool and popular (but this is for another discussion lol). but 1 thing that i wanna highlight is this one particular manga called "OUT".

Out is a manga written by Tatsuya Iguchi and illustrated by Makoto Mizuta. Tatsuya was inspired by a novel called "DROP" by Hiroshi Shinagawa and also his own experience when he was entangled with a motorcycle club in chiba. the manga itself tells a story about 17-year-old Iguchi Tatsuya that has been released from juvenile detention and trying to get away from the bad influence of his old friends, but he's still find himself in trouble and having a tendencies to violence as well. all and all, your typical school fighting manga like clover and crows.

"so, what's the correlation between the manga and CH?" glad that u asked. if u take a look at the cover of the manga, you can see the character of the manga itself was rocking chrome all over their body. their cover arts is basically a lookbook fr. they really feature some of the classic silhouettes like filigree cross, keeper ring, and even the Rolex sub with roller bracelet. the amount of details and accessories everyone use in 1 cover is also crazy. they stack it like Wisdom Kaye's Instagram content, while existing since 2012. they way they draw it is also aesthetically pleasing. they really draw it like its just another details. it feels like they do really rocking the brand and fit the aesthetic, not only wearing it for the drip.

all and all, go check out the manga. its pretty good and i actually just discover this manga like couple days ago. so... have fun!

Content:
NOW THAT I'VE BEEN TALKING NICE ABOUT CHROME, i guess it's time to slander them for a bit. I KNOWWW how the public may love this brand whatever they do, but just for a minute, take a look at this monstrosity and lemme know what u think aight.

so this one is a collaboration between chrome hearts, nocta, and nike. they basically create a puffer jacket and others like crewneck and t-shirts. the collaboration itself is pretty wild, since nocta has been moving crazy in 2025. they literally do collaborations with everyone at this point, ranging from SP5DER, Venezia FC, CODE 05, and now, chrome hearts. this collab works suppose to be a big and amazing things, since drake himself has been hinting on the works and also hyping it up, telling us that this is his biggest fashion collab of 2025. but what i see from the release? an actual garbage. a failed attempt to utilize a popular and high demand silhouette tbh.

i know that something like a realtree or hunting camouflage has been popular for the past few weeks. i know that this is basically 3 huge brands colliding. i also realize that this could be something popular in 2026, but tbh with you, i don't fw it. i hate it. it's ugly. like, when they're trying to incorporate the chrome cross on the pattern, it looks hideous for me. the overall silhouette is also not really helping. the silver zip is too small to be a main point of the design, and the puffer is also a normal nike puffer. i don't think i can justify the $39.000 price tag for this one fr. i feel like, they're trying too hard. they're combining things that don't really belong to one another and just ended up creating a failure imho. i usually love the realtree graphic hat and tees, but this one is garbage fr. i dunno how to defend it tbh lol

all and all, i will say that PROBABLY, this goes hard for someone, but not me. if me in 2025 hate this collab, let's see in 10 years if i yearn for this product, bcs i know some people that suddenly fw supreme box hoodie in '25

Author: lotso125
Content:
some people do love to buy vintage or second hand clothes for various reasons. some did it bcs it was cheaper or trying to sell it for a higher price. others did it because of the age, or more specifically, the rugged look of the clothes itself, or so called "patina". but what is patina?

so, patina is a natural, gradual surface change on materials like metal, wood, or leather, resulting from aging, use, and exposure to elements that creates a unique sheen, color shift, motifs, and texture. people love patina because it tells a story of how long did someone wear that specific piece of clothing, and how long does it takes to "create" one. some of the more common patinas in fashion cultures are honeycomb jeans, faded fabrics, matured raw leathers, and worn-down clothes. people love patina so much, they create an idea called "trompe l'oeil", where they create fake stains age and wear on their freshly made clothes, eventho its very different from a "true" patina where it can only shown after years of usage.

me personally, i love to create patina. i've done so many things from maturing my leather wallet, ripping my old jeans, sea wash raw denims, putting coins on my pocket and brush it using a nail file, dropping cigs ashes on my hoodie, and so on lmao. i will say, i do enjoy waiting for it, taking care of the products, and also trying to faster things up bcs i'm impatient like that. but truly, the experience of creating your patina is amazing and also unique for me, bcs the idea of wearing the same pants for years just to create a honeycomb on my calves and have your phones marked in your pants is just cool. i think personally, patina is always great, and it does tells a lot of stories, especially if you love that 1 clothing piece like that.

all and all, i do recommend you guys to create your own patinas on your fashion items. if you're impatient like me, either google how to create the fade and marks, or buy that $550 carhartt jacket from your local vintage store lol

Author: lotso125
Content:
today isn't about fashion or alcohol (which seems to be the main topics of this forum). today ill talk abt my long-lasting internal hatred towards some invisible lines, which is the international date line.

basically, international date line (IDL)  is an imaginary line, mostly along the 180¬∞ longitude in the pacific ocean, that separates one calendar day from the next, essentially marking where a new day begins (westward) and an old one ends (eastward). crossing it westward adds a day (you go back in time, sort of), while crossing eastward subtracts a day (moving forward in time), helping reconcile global time zones. we need the IDL to prevent global time chaos, acting as the 24-hour boundary where a new calendar day begins and ends, allowing for consistent time zones as the earth rotates.

my main issue with IDL is that, it's not a straight line. its full of zigs and zags, and it just didn't really make any sense to me. basically, IDL isn't straight to avoid splitting countries, islands, and territories, preventing major confusion where one side of a community could be a day ahead of the other. IDL basically splitting earth into two like the equator, but because some countries are PUSSIES that didn't want to be confused with different calendar days, WE HAVE CORNERS IN OUR IDL. i hate it bcs SOME COUNTRIES like SAMOA and ALEUTIAN ISLANDS are being a COWARD and really said "boo hoo pls dont let our SMALL islands hv different dates uwu :3" all i see is countries being a LOSER that just really thinks that THEY'RE IMPORTANTS (they are, sometimes). YOUR BIGGEST EXPOSURE IS THE .tv WEB EXTENTION (yes i'm talking to u, tuvalu) and MUN KIDS REPPING YOUR COUNTRIES BCS THEY LITERALLY DIDN'T HAVE ANY OPTIONS.

all and all, IDL is important and very helpful towards our live, but can we agree to pray that KIRIBATI, TONGA, SAMOA, and FIJI to SINK FASTER so that we can have a straight IDL? thank you so much this has been lotso's TedTalk

Author: lotso125
Content:
we've seen this photo before, whether as an aura farming meme inspiration, something that u want to put in your house because of "aesthetic" purposes, or simply because it's the moment of the birth of a fashion icon. yes, this photo is about Yves Saint Laurent (YSL) grieving on the funeral of his mentor, which also happened to be the legendary Christian Dior.

Dior died of a heart attack back in october 24th, 1957 in montecatini, italy. it was a sudden news for everyone since he was on vacation that day. some reports said that he was dead while choking on a fish bone, others said that he died of heart attack after playing cards. YSL, who was his prot√©g√© at that moment, basically was mourning his teacher when the picture was taken. it wasn't a "marketing campaign" or a "symbol of the future", it was all sadness. YSL also stated his admirations towards his mentor, and how he can't be a couturier if not because of dior himself. really, a national event.

after i've done my research, i feel like this photo is actually more powerful than i ever imagine. YSL basically was informed in the middle of the ceremony that he'll be the successor of christian dior, and the artistic director of the haute couture house at only 21 years old. that was some HEAVY burden to begin with. think of it as a CEO, or a leader of the WHOLE fashion genre at such tender age. not only that, YSL also need to carry dior's name through the highest critics from fashion journalists such as vogues and harper's bazaar which at that time, was a very huge deal to begin with (still to this day ofc). but dior maybe knows more than anyone, since he also highly praise YSL since he was 18 years old. dior actually said that "*Yves Saint Laurent is young, but he is an immense talent. In my last collection, I consider him to be the father of thirty-four out of the 180 designs. I think the time has come to reveal it to the press. My prestige won‚Äôt suffer from it*" which is the

Author: lotso125
Content:
highest compliment that someone in fashion could receive in my opinion. bcs cmon now, dior said that to you? damn ts crazy fr. but then again, even though he was mourning to the death of his mentor and friend, he still there, stood tall. he really understand the burdens that was left to him, that it has to be him, the youngest couturier in the world, who capable enough to carry the name of christian dior himself.

all and all, all i can say is that i love this photo since the first time i saw it back in middle school. i do used to think that it was only a random dude with a weird name, mourning the death of some other dude in a cool way. i guess every photos have some importance in them huh. one more thing tho, christian dior's next collection in 1958 was a huge success. YSL receive a standing ovation, and all the press' that was attending the show was left amazed and "in a state of euphoria" according to the Mus√©e Yves Saint Laurent Paris. they were attempting to immortalize the debut of the ‚Äúlittle prince of fashion,‚Äù while groups of admirers wept with joy.

Author: lotso125
Content:
different peoples are belong to different fandoms. from e-sports to F1, people do love different types of niches because ofc, they hv different interests. but one thing for sure, there's a certain trends that really influenced how people cheer or support their idols, which is kpop, or more specifically, kpopification of fandoms. so what is kpopification?

The "kpopification" of a fandom is the adoption of K-pop's unique and highly organized fan  culture, aesthetics, and interaction models by fans of non-K-pop entities. basically, this is how trends like fan projects, usage of slangs (trainee, maknae, and bias), fancams & edits, merchandises such as photocards, and community identities were emerged inside of the fandoms. some people love it, and some people hate it. i remembered reading some arguments from a valorant champions called zeek, where he said that the trend is detrimental to the competitive integrity and cultures of the game itself, linking to toxic and overly parasocial behaviors that they feel detract from the game itself. some people also argue with the growing numbers of female fans in F1, which used to be a male dominated sport for a long time. they said that kpopifications kinda ruin the sport that they love. they argued that the sport has shifted from the strategy and technical aspects to the luxury and drama side of the sport, which was unimportant before. i will say, i've seen some FOMO F1 fans that only follow certain teams and being toxic to the fans of other teams, which was really makes no sense and wasn't happened before (i think).

personally, i guess kpopification in fandoms are okay. both are industries that trying to create more money, and also trying to be more relevant each and every day. if anything, kpop fans do know how to create buzz and traction towards their idols, while the og fandoms can also always focus on the sports or anything that they love, without bothering one another.

Author: lotso125
Content:
to kick off 2026, i think i'll start with a story of someone that really grinds her way to money, success, and fame. this is the story of Nanami Hashimoto (Nanamin)

Nanamin is a former member of Nogizaka46. she was active in 2011 and graduated in 2017. after graduating, she retired from entertainment industries, study spatial design in tokyo, and now working at sony music entertainment as a music video producer. her career history is nothing out of the ordinary, i guess. a lot of idols that graduated do retired from the industry altogether, but what make her special is why she choose to be an idol from the first place. she admit that she started to be an idol because she wants to pay her parents debt. even as an idol, she still juggles multiple part-time and university works. she even considering graduate early to apply as a civil servant or lawyer just because she needs more money. at one of her show, she admit that at her house, "Gas, water, and electricity were cut off on a daily basis due to nonpayment of bills." and that was her main goal of being an idol at the first place. after six years with the group, she announced her graduation simply because she repaid all of her parents debt already. it was a teary announcement as well since her parents was sending her a letter contains their regret of making her working that hard and always pushing herself, and how she basically turn their lives around to the better. her brother also make an appearance and saying that he's proud of his sister and how he's eligible for an academic scholarship because her sister always supported his dream and never let the electricity out. i swear to you, i actually shed a manly tears watching all of that graduation concert.

all and all, her story is one for the book, because she is very resilient and hard-working that ur actually respect her grind. so goodluck, nanamin. keep enjoying murakami's works and shine brighter than anyone else.

Author: lotso125
Content:
collecting vinyls is fun, because a lot of them have a unique shape, pattern, and sleeve design that just amazing to look at. but one day, i was looking at instagram and saw a particular style of vinyl, which is liquid filled vinyl. what is it and why it's trending now?

when i first saw this, i thought that this is a newly made idea that turned out to be cool. it was the vinyl for the soundtrack of the movie "saltburn" that makes me aware to such style of vinyl. i thought this was a new invention, but that wasn't the case. in fact, disney thought of it first back in 1978, but it was failed because there's a leakage and sealing issues that makes them prevented the release. the early method of liquid filled vinyl was to glue record halves with a spacer after filling the gap with a colored liquid. this leads to inconsistencies, leakage, evaporation, and poor sound quality due to the non-standard construction.

in the modern era, people finally crack how to create a more durable way to seal liquid filled vinyl. basically what they do is to swap the liquid inside of the vinyl to this oily, sticky liquid that kinda looks like a slime. they did this to prevent wet leakage and evaporation of the liquid itself. after that, they use special resin and airtight seals to improve the sealings of the halves, making sure that the vinyl itself have a better overall qualities, playable with a better sound, and also longer storage life so that stores and collectors didn't have to worry. after the improvements, people started to go crazy with the theme of the liquid itself. some bands mixed their blood into the vinyl, some mixing sands and hairs into theirs, and saltburn...... yeah i have no comment on saltburn's vinyl liquid lmao.

all and all, this is a very cool inventions imho. some collectors do argue that this type of vinyl is only a marketing gimmick since they have less audio quality, higher cost to make, and only serve a purpose of being a display, which i kinda agree

Author: lotso125
Content:
if u fw air jordans like me, u gotta realize that jordans got tons of different colors on the shoes. from red and black colorway to the all white ones, almost every air jordan have their own nicknames, and some of those nicknames have their own origin stories. so here's some of air jordan's nickname that i know.

- Bred: Any Air Jordan in the basic Chicago Bulls black and red colorway. used to be banned because back then NBA only allowed white shoes

- Black/white Cement: The black/white-speckled grey paneling that was found as an accent. originated in air jordan 4, but the air jordan 3 version of it shows something like a "crack" on some panels.

- Chicago: almost like the bred colorway, but with a touch of white in the midbody and midsole

- Pollen: black and yellow colorway, inspired by bees

- Shattered Backboard: inspired by a famous moment in 1985 when Michael Jordan shattered a backboard with a dunk during a Nike exhibition game in Italy. black and orange colorway

- UNC: short for University of North Carolina, which is MJ's alma mater. they use baby blue and white colorway inspired by the color of the UNC's jersey

- Concord: Refers to the 'White/Black/Dark Concord' colorway of the Air Jordan 11

- Cool grey: characterized by a mostly medium grey upper with white accents

- Shadow: almost like cool grey, but with darker grey and black colorway

- Flu Game: exclusively air jordan 12 with bred colorway. famous because MJ played in this shoe while having food poisoning

- Georgetown: navy and gray colorway inspired by MJ‚Äôs famed game winner against the school in the 1982 NCAA Championship

- Royal: royal blue and black colorway, which apparently MJ's favorite color combination

- LA to Chicago: mostly purple and gold, that wears out to chicago colorway once it aged and scuffed.

that's (probably) all the colorways that i know with their original stories as well. it's still an incomplete list ofc, so lemme know if u know more alright?

Author: lotso125
Content:
usually, dating shows are full of awkward talks, people with a very huge egos, and contestants just there trying to "get down". this one is... a bit different, and i find it interesting. im talking about "Badly in Love".

Badly in Love is a japanese dating shows filled with group of men and women with checkered pasts living in an old school building for two weeks; at the end of that time, they have to declare their love for one of their housemates. im talking about ex yakuza, club owner, hostess, and biker gang leader participating in a dating show (yes their pasts is real) and just really trying to build a relationship lol. i remember watching just the first 2 minutes of the first episodes and 2 of the contestants are already fighting. they even have securities and bodyguards in the shows to protect their casts from fights and anything else, which is crazy. if you knew dating shows like terrace house, single's inferno, or love island, this was very different from it. i feel like, they're being very honest about themselves. they speak bluntly about attraction, irritation and insecurity, skipping the sugarcoating common to the genre, which really shows the rawness and genuineness of their feelings as well to the viewers. they also have strict rules like no physical violence and no illegal activities, which if broken could basically send them home lol. other things that i love about this series is also how the contestants, with their turbulent pasts and all, reveal unexpected depth as they open up about trauma, regret and attempts to change course, which i kinda get. idk why, but i love how genuine they was, how earnest every confessions feels like, and also how emotional some people could be. i really enjoy this series i guess lol.

all and all, i think this is one of the better dating show that u can watch next time, and it's very enjoyable as well. lemme know if u also enjoy it or want to discuss this topic even more aight?

Author: lotso125
Content:
should've done this earlier this month, but oh well better late than never lol. this is just a ramble about people who said that 2026 is just the new 2016, while thinking that 2016 was the "peak" year for trends. me personally, i don't think that 2016 was "that" good as a year to talk about fashion and culture to begin with. i mean like, let's be real. 2025 was the hit, it was probably one of the most entertaining years for fashion. we literally started the year with adidas "tang" jacket, wearing labubu as a bag charms, the rise of performative matcha male, and who can't forget all of those marty supreme collection?

in retrospect, 2016 wasn't all about it. see, you think Kanye's "the life of pablo" capsule was great? do you think that supreme box hoodie was amazing? do you think that wearing a choker and ankle boots was great? i dunno about that buddy. oh, Dries Van Noten was releasing a bomber jacket? AGAIN? wow so creative wow so real! VLONE tees and off white yellow belt? wow much color sign me up i guess. Vetements DHL tees? meh. but that's enough about fashion, and let's see other trends in 2016 such as "WORK" by Rihanna, "LEAN ON" by Major Lazer, "ROSES" by The Chainsmoker, "HOTLINE BLING" by Drake, like, that's some repetitive ahh music and also, a BORING one. yes i said it. a boring one. we also can't forget other things like snapchat dog filter, Instagram's Valencia and Clarendon filters, #swag on every post, Conjuring and Deadpool was reigning supreme at cinemas like, what's up with all of those??? that's so cringe i actually can't lmao.

i guess, 2016 wasn't all bad. yes i do kinda missed those years in my life, and yes i still crave those yeezy 900 and nike more uptempo, and yes i do still love to listen to calvin harris, but idk.... i think cringing towards the past is not that bad.... and i think i was accidentally listing all of my favorite things in 2016 so..... yeah..... hehe

Author: lotso125
Content:
i actually find peace in disorganized places, but idk why. its basically what i felt ever since i sleep in my own room, and i always keep my room messy all the time. im the type of person that remember where did i place (almost) everything i owned and i never feel any sense of urgency to just declutter or simply tidy up my room (unless it's my bed, i hate rugged sheets lmao). but yeah, having a messy rooms kinda put me in peace, since i feel like, that's really what it feels inside of me. i can have tons of boxes and shelves in my room, and still kinda put everything on my table, just because. as i was typing this, i actually was surrounded by my pc setup, tissue boxes, stickers, and magazines that i just never really bothered to clean up.

when i look it up, apparently, i was leaning towards type B personality, which usually generalized as an easy-going, relaxed person. they said that type b people kinda mess their workplace or comfortable places because it's where their creativity really running on. they said that it was because they're really focused with something in front of them, and not really bothered with their surroundings, making their spaces feels cramped and untidy. honestly, i can see that, because all i need is to make sure that my keyboard and screen wasnt covered with anything and im gucci like that. i dont care if i havent put my albums in the wardrobe, or whether my xy kidz magazine was on the floor, as long as my laptop and/or pc wasnt getting disturbed lol. i know this isnt the best thing to discover, but yeah it kinda happened.

all and all, while writing this ramble,  i also tidying up my space, and i must say, not a bad job from me tbh. i managed to actually put everything where they belong, and also feel a bit accomplished that i managed to actually keep my shit together as i was working lol. i do hope that i can continue this positive trends and actually clean up my desk better, and hope u guys also get inspired to clean ur rooms as well.

Author: lotso125
Content:
i love to see cosplays, because a lot of em really get creative and in theme with the character theyre cosplaying. but today, i will talk about the oguri cap cosplay trend.

so if u didnt know who oguri cap is, she's one of the real horse race in japan, and also a chara from uma musume: pretty derby. she can be characterized by diamond tiara on her head, short white hair, and also gluttony behavior. in the anime, she often be seen chomping huge amount of foods and also constantly hungry, which really explains why i love this trend of cosplay.

basically, i was surfing on the internet when i saw the oguri cap ordering from burger king drive thru cosplay. at first i was, cackled by how on theme the cosplay was, and also how seemingly "effortless" they look. aside from the intricate wigs and school uniform, i feel like, this oguri cap cosplay is one of my favorite thing to see, because of all the things that really make the scene. after that one drive thru cosplay, i also saw a lot of them posing in front of the burger king, eating the whopper, rocking the paper crown, and also just vibing, really capturing the essence of the character. i know that a lot of cosplayers also goes thru lengths to create realistic cosplays such as climbing a mountain and doing photoshoot at the beach, but this one is different for me. burger king, unlike other spots, are kinda everywhere, and spotting one wouldn't be so difficult imho. its just really shows that u know your chara really well, and you execute the photoshoot perfectly eventho it's just probably a block or two from your house. burger king and oguri cap is a combination that i kinda associate together with, and i guess any more oguri cap cosplays wouldn't be complete without the signature burger and paper crown i'm afraid.

all and all, i really enjoy watching and looking at those oguri cap cosplayers, and i'd like to see more goofy uma musume cosplay from now on. and yes, i support uma musume cosplay at the broncos' games lol

Author: lotso125
Content:
i like whimsical luxury items that really have little to no purposes (beside their actual purposes) and i'd like to talk about it today.

basically what i mean with whimsical items was some "useless", cheaper items that u buy because u need to build relationship with the brands. for example, before you can buy Audemars Piguet's (AP) Royal Oak Perpetual Calendar, u need to buy other, cheaper watches from AP so that you can be "trusted" by the brand to buy their more luxury, expensive, rare, and sought after products, like the royal oak. for other brands like Hermes, you can't immediately buy the Kelly or the Birkin bags, instead you can get yourself other bags, ties, even some stationaries from them. in AP's case, cheaper watches are still a good product, is just that you can't buy some of the rarer APs, but in Hermes' case, why the hell would you need a, orange colored pencil case with a horse logo? but people still did this, because ‚ú® Birkins ‚ú®. ~~eventho you can always buy secondhand birkins from consignment stores just don't forget to legit check them tho~~

but tbh, some of those whimsical items were also really cool and i'd love to get my hands on them. like those pencils are cool. YSL lomo camera is cool. Chrome Hearts' sauce bottles are cool. even things that are too whimsical like Supreme's Brick and crowbars are cool. idk why, but i do fell in love with them. it's just too goofy to pass on to. i feel like, i can show it off to my friends that "yes i do own some avant garde, high-fashion, luxury items as well" while they're wondering whether it's gonna be a 3-piece suit from Prada or just some Chrystal Chess Set from Baccarat. it's just cool, y'know? and yeah i do understand that i might be senseless or anything but to own something so silly like this to decorate my own space is just like a funny dreams to chase after lol.

all and all, that's what i think about whimsical, luxury items. please share more goofy things from your favorite luxury brands!
