Author: lotso125
Content:
idk if you realize it or not, but LOEWE has changed its logo effective January 2026. so, what happened?

so i kinda noticed the new logo from their F/W pre collections, which really, also raised a lot of questions from the people. Loewe's logo used to be this 4 mirrored Ls shaped like a square, and now they only consist of a pair of Ls. even those Ls doesn't mean as an L, but as an L and a J, which stands for Lazaro Hernandez and Jack McCollough, their new creative directors. since Jonathan Anderson's departure to DIOR, Loewe is being led by both Lazaro and Jack at the helm. beyond their partnership as a creative directors, apparently they're also a real life couple. whether the resemblance is intentional or coincidental, nobody knows tbh with you. but the "timing" and the subtlety of the move make this thought hard to ignore imho. tbh it feels like less like a branding and more like a human signature for me. really marking the change of their directions from the usual, marking of the luxury Spanish brand, to something more intimate, and classy. the old logo itself was designed in 1970s by Spanish artist Vicente Vela, build from 4 mirrored Ls and arranged into a continuous knot. back then, it references the branding irons of leather ateliers and the ornamental language of Spanish crafts.

if you ask me, this isn't something new. luxury brands like YSL and Balmain also experimenting new logos for their brands. what makes Loewe different for me was the way they didn't change the Spanish artistry from their logo to something more minimalistic and boring like what YSL did. they didn't just slap a lousy Montserrat or Times New Roman logo on their brands and called it a day lol. instead they still embrace their Spanish heritage, and just refresh their looks from their logo, just to make it more short and subtle, just like their new collections. overall, i kinda like it, and i can't wait for their big S/S collection reveal that people said "jaw-dropping" and "refreshing".

Author: lotso125
Content:
2026 kicks in with so many cool things, and this car modification is one of them. and all i can say is that Rocket Bunny, u did it again mf

if u didn't know, Rocket Bunny is a renowned line of Japanese widebody car kits designed by Kei Miura of TRA Kyoto, known for their aggressive, rivet-style overfenders and, often, retro-inspired aesthetics. if you've been playing games like Forza and NFS, u must know that the widebody trends are first popularized by Rocket Bunny as well and they're heavily influenced by them.

Rocket Bunny has done tons of modifications, but this one is too cute that i can't pass them up. so basically, they modified a Suzuki Twin kei car to make it look like a Skyline GT-R. they custom made and specifically create this small, full body kit that shaped like an R-32 GT-R complete with headlights, exaggerated fender flares, a scaled rear wing and even period-correct 8-spoke wheels and sponsor decals. its shaped like a Japanese model car toy called "Choro-Q", hence the nickname and the name of this project. this car made its 1st appearance at Tokyo Auto Salon and quite literally create a huge buzz upon its launch. when the show literally happened, all i can see on my timeline was this car, and to be honest, i love this mods. this works really create something unexpected bcs like, nobody will suspect something small like Suzuki Twin could be modified to something like this. i also love how cute and silly it is. when u hear Rocket Bunny, ur gonna immediately thinking about miatas, RX-7s, silvias, and other JDM staples. i guess Suzuki Twin is still a Japanese car for sure, but yknow... not one of the staple base car and ofc also not something ur gonna expect.

all and all, this car is basically the epitome of Japanese car culture, referencing JDM legend ‚Äì the R32 GT-R, relatability ‚Äì kei cars as a staple vehicle option for Japanese commuters, and Pop culture ‚Äì the "Choro Q" nickname and build reference, which is very cool imho.

Author: lotso125
Content:
the chic is back with JW Anderson as Dior's creative director, and i will say, this spring would be exciting for the brand itself. i know that i'm a bit late for this, but so far, all i can see is that how JW Anderson kinda revolutionize Dior for having a lot of loud branding in their design to something more quiet, more subtle, and again, more chic.

so i've seen Dior's S/S 2026 women collection, and immediately, i saw Anderson's way of reviving Dior's long lost elegance. in the past years, Dior's collection was a bit, redundant and loud if i'm being honest. Anderson himself calling his wave as something "radical", where he also said "Radical doesn‚Äôt have to be loud; radical can sometimes just be about the process of trying to work out what is new, and what is new for Dior is different from what would be new for Loewe.‚Äù as someone who used to be Loewe's creative director, this is something a little bit shocking, because he kinda trying to create a distinction where Dior is this "wasteland" where he could create his own universe and not being afraid to destroy any tradition unlike his previous workplace.

the difference in design do be very apparent. his take on Dior's newest collection feels like an explosion of creativities where he kinda do what he was limited to where he's in Loewe. i was amazed by his usage of oversize hats, puff skirts, and satin shirts that not only scream elegance, but also chic at the same time. i also love the fact that Anderson use small details to promote the brandings, unlike their previous collections. you can see Dior's tag hidden or written very small on the ornaments like bow and straps, and i can't get enough of those designs. his lady dior campaign also looks good with the emphasis on what and how being a lady is. pushing the narrative of everyone is and could be one.

all and all, i think Anderson will do a good job in Dior, and hopefully he could retain the popularities of the brand itself. i mean he better be lmao.

Author: lotso125
Content:
these days, i actually have been captivated by 2 of these watches and i must say, those things are pretty af and i'd love to own either one of them in the future.

so the 1st one is Lady Arpels Heures Florales Cerisier watch from Van Cleef. this 38mm watch was created with luxury gems such as diamonds, sapphires, and mother pearls and made to resemble a flower on beds of vine. i do aware its functionalities as a watch are a bit confusing, but nonetheless, a cool watch to look at. i mean, the way of telling time with this one is to count the number of open flowers on the dial to determine the hour (1 to 12), while the minutes are displayed via a small window on the side of the case. beauty against practicalities, amirite.

the 2nd watch is actually function more like a normal watch, but it's still one for the book i guess. it is Vacheron Constantin's Heures CreÃÅatives Heure DiscreÃÄte. this one comes from their Heures Cr√©atives collection, which was inspired by the women‚Äôs watches developed by the actual Vacheron Constantin during the 1920s, 1930s and 1970s. the inspiration behind the design clearly comes from a fan that commonly used in both european and asian culture, decorated with 18k diamonds and also manual winding for the watch itself. one hell of a watch that's for sure.

all and all, yes i'm aware that this watch were made for women of at least, created with women user in mind, i just feel like, i can't help but to look at it as a piece of beautiful jewelry at the end of the day, i mean, amidst its design, purpose, and practicality, i still love those watches and can see myself actually wearing one on my wrist. sometimes, design for male audiences can be a little... monotonous, boring, lackluster, and dull yknow? and this watch, as feminine as it is, still put me in a chokehold and still makes me begging for it. f those guys that say boys don't deserve cute things. so... yeah that's all. let me know which watches you'd love to have in your life, i guess?

Author: lotso125
Content:
More kpop members are becoming ambassador of brands, and that "achievements" are enough to basically let their fans boost their ego on social media. but what if instead of just wearing the brand, they also collaborating with the said brands? this is the story of one of the biggest custom made piece created by one of the biggest jeweler in the world for one of the biggest talent in kpop.

Jacob & Co. collaborated with G-DRAGON to create the ‚ÄúBandana Royale,‚Äù a one of a kind (get it? lol) jeweled collar weighing 559.3 grams in 18K yellow gold, designed for his √úbermensch World Tour and 2025 Melon Music Award. this piece features 209.71 carats of gemstones, anchored by a 5.40-carat Fancy Yellow diamond at the center of a jeweled daisy, and embellished with over 2,000 white diamonds, rubies, emeralds, and multi-colored sapphires. this sculptural piece reinterprets G-DRAGON‚Äôs signature bandana styling into an innovative statement of high jewelry, also anchoring the intricate form of a jeweled daisy, a motif synonymous with G-DRAGON‚Äôs creative philosophy and brand, PEACEMINUSONE. this collab is not a big surprise tbh with you, since G-DRAGON has been collaborating with Jacob & Co before, creating a PEACEMINUSONE logo jewelry and also The Astronomia Solar G-Dragon watch, solidifying his creative inputs and aspects within the brand. eventho their collab just happened from 2025, we all can see how the brand trust G-DRAGON with his own vision, giving him so much freedom as an artist to basically creates some of the coldest pieces in 2025. 

imho, this is a big milestone in kpop history, because this also opens more possibilities of idols receiving their own collaboration with luxury brands. this used to be a luxury only westerners can enjoy, but G-DRAGON basically making it possible for Korean idols to be involved on creative process of creating their own collabs or line of products for western luxury items. he literally paved the way and no other arguments can say otherwise.

Author: lotso125
Content:
"it's too early for a gimlet" is a famous line from The Long Goodbye, one of a classic books written by Raymond Chandler. what does that mean?

before i talk about the line, let's talk about gimlet. gimlet is a name of a cocktail that traditionally made out of gin and lime cordial. some says that the name gimlet comes from a tool used to drill small holes because the cocktail also cause some "stinging" after effect to its drinker, and some also says that it comes from the royal navy. there are also variations of gimlet, such as vodka gimlet and pimmlet.

enough about gimlet, but what is "it's too early for a gimlet"? just like what i said earlier, this line derives from a novel written by Raymond Chandler. it tells a story of a husband that find out his wife was actually murdered, and a detective trying to solve the case (which is really classic back in the day) (mind you this novel was like, published in the 50s or something). the phrase "it's too early for a gimlet" was said by the husband to the detective, signifies their friendship and, later, the haunting memory of their shared moments. the husband said this, because they both agree to drink gimlet to forget everything that happened, and just walk separately. but instead, he said that because as painful as the memories is, he don't want to forget it, wanting to preserve it as another bond that was formed because of his wife's death.

but another usage of "it's too early for a gimlet" can commonly be found in Japanese bars, where a lot of senior bartenders and customers tend to use this words to their subordinates or rookie bartender to signifies that they're not ready to mix or make gimlet yet, signaling their lack of bartending experiences. from one interview that i watch (and also from a manga) it was simply a reminder, that bartender need to keep practicing and studying so that they can always be better.

so yeah... thats all i know about it. lemme know if u want more discussions about alcohol (yippeeee)!

Content:
so... apparently there are few different Michelin awards with different standards and logos to identify, and here are some of them.

the first one is Michelin stars. this is probably the most common sign and also the most praised and sought after symbol a restaurant can get. it varies from 1 star to 3 star (yeah Felix of straykids was wrong about this), and each stars also mean different things. basically, restaurants may receive One to Three Michelin stars for the quality of their food based on five criteria: quality of the ingredients used, mastery of flavor and cooking techniques, the personality of the chef in the cuisine, harmony of flavors, and consistency between visits. 1 star means its worth a stop, 2 stars means worth a detour, and 3 stars means worth a journey. other than the 3 categories there's also green star that acknowledge restaurateur that at the forefront of sustainable gastronomy.

the next one is Comfort and Quality, which also being scored by Michelin's journalist. for restaurants, it's symbolized by spoon and fork, while the other one is for accommodations like hotels that symbolized by house and trees. there are 5 levels into this comfortable level, which ranges from quite comfortable, comfortable, very comfortable, top class comfort, and luxury.

there's also Bib Gourmand, which given to friendly establishments that serve good food at moderate prices depending the country and areas. so this one is not like a consolation prize or anything, but it's they way of Michelin praising restaurateurs dedicated to providing authentic dining experiences by way of quality cuisine at affordable prices in approachable and friendly establishments. this award symbolized by the Michelin Man licking it lips.

there are also other symbols such as recommended, notable wine/beer/cocktail list, interesting view, terrace dining, simple shop, and counter dining which really makes it easier for customers to read their guides. that's all i know, and happy eating!

Author: lotso125
Content:
if you're listening to a lot of j-pop, u might know this band called ASIAN KUNG-FU GENERATION (AKFG). but today, I'm not gonna talk about their stories or my favorite songs, no. I'm gonna talk about the man behind their CD jacket or CD cover designs, which is Yusuke Nakamura.

so Yusuke Nakamura is a Japanese illustrator, manga artist, and musician. he was graduated from the design major of Osaka University of Arts with dreams of working at a game company. after graduated from there, he served as an assistant in his major while actively working as an illustrator. he was working for some time, until he was invited to his first solo exhibitions where he was made public for the first time. around the same year, Masafumi Gotoh from AKFG also contacted him to illustrate their debut album called H≈çkai Amplifier, and the rest is history.

what i like about his illustrations is how he used clean lines, flat colors, and also his "character" that usually a depiction of a women with this still-faced image that for me, either looks like innocence, or just complete no reaction almost. Nakamura's philosophy for AKFG's cover album while designing their CD jacket was to explaining the feelings of the songs in the album subtly, hence the still face of his character while usually accompanied with "louder" surroundings and backgrounds. it do feels like he was creating this whole world and spaces where he imagine what the album looks like, before you're listening to the first song. the fact that AKFG and Nakamura already worked together for so long is also amazed me. you can't think of one without the other, and this create this mutual connection in this zeitgeist, which was awesome.

all and all, now you know who's the man behind almost every AKFG's CD jacket. for more Yusuke Nakamura's art, I'll also put his works collaborating with Bocchi The Rock to commemorate their first arena one-man live concert of Kessoku Band. enjoy!

Author: lotso125
Content:
last time i was covering Michelin's awards for the most prestigious restaurant in your area. while i was researching, i found out that Thailand also have their own awards for restaurants that trusted by locals because of their consistency and quality. this is Shell Chuan Chim.

Shell Chuan Chim award was first established in 1961 by Thanadsri Svasti, a Thai writer, singer, and actor but famously know as food journalist and reviewer for this panel. the story was Prince Bhisadej Rajani, a marketing manager at Shell Thailand at the time, approached Thanadsri to help create a soft advertising campaign for its newly launched cooking gas products. Inspired by the Michelin Guide, they came up with the idea of a food review column, to be written by Thanadsri and sponsored by Shell, and named it "Shell Chuan Chim" which translated to "Shell urges you to taste". Thanadsri travelled throughout the country, visiting restaurants and recommending venues that offered great-tasting food, and became known as a guarantee of excellence, and was extremely influential, since they're featured and also putting up the Shell Chuan Chim sign.

there's actually a website for their records and list of restaurants in Thailand, but i can't read it because it was all in Thai and i can't read one lol. but if you're interested, u can check them out at https://shellshuanshim.com/ for more information regarding their scoring system, their yearly recap, and also list of must visits while you're in certain areas. or maybe, you can also hunt for the bowl sign, which is Shell Chuan Chim's logo. their logo was this white bowl with green details, and also there's some thai underneath translated to "Welcome to Taste" in red. i don't think you will missed it lol.

all and all, i think this is pretty cool for your own country to have their own restaurants grading systems. because tbh with you, i don't think we should trust influencers that only focused on "instagrammable" and "aesthetic" restaurants lol.

Author: lotso125
Content:
i think we romanticized smoking too much, but for some reason, i like it.

so I'm a smoker, right. and i think as a human, whether you're a smoker or not, i think we tend to romanticize smoking too much. we kinda put smoking into this "light" where we see cigarette as a cool thing, even where smoking was known for its addiction and illness inducing thing. for example, we kinda identify cigarettes with cool things thanks to their branding like cowboys, fast cars, masculinity, extreme actions, survivals, and others. other branding forms of cigarettes also included in memes, where a lot of people talk about "smoking like parisienne type of way" or "European breakfast" and "girl/boy dinner". even branded things also including smoking in mind, Casio's CRW-001, Dolce & Gabbana ashtray, even S.T. Dupont's entire accessories ideas, all derived from those activities.

if you ask me personally, i don't think i hate it, because i think everything and anything could be an aesthetic or "mood" in a way. a lot of us do think about it, not necessarily because we partake in those activities, but only because it looks cool, and cool things are everywhere. as a human, we are inspired by things around us, and it's only natural that cigarettes are counted to be one of those. we romanticized those things because we put that things into tons of perspective, whether its about life, love, pain, and others. one stick of cigarettes could be symbolized into anything that you feel, and symbolism is everywhere. its not a mere "sickness in a box" for me. i do think that it really symbolize one part of my life that i want to cherish, whether it was the first one i burned, the first one i shared with my friends, the fire i light with loved ones, the last butt i stomped outside of a bar in senopati, and other things. cigarettes really walks me down through the memory lanes, and it's not a bad thing at all.

probably smoking is what i have left, and i feel empty without it. but really, i don't care.

Author: lotso125
Content:
these days, probably since last year, i enjoy collecting coasters from various cafes and restaurants. this obsession started when i was switching my old working desk for a new one. i used to use this good old plastic table to work, but since 2022 i switch my table to a wooden top with metal supports (this is kinda important i swear). as long as i know, wooden table is a bit hassle to take care, since they could worn out because of so many things such as termites, water, and so on. since i often put my cold drinks on the table, i feel the need to own a coaster or anything to basically prevent the water to leave a mark on the table, and thats how this obsession started.

at first i bought a set of cork coasters from ikea. it was a good and durable one, but a bit boring tbh. it has no design, colors, or just anything unique and it kinda becoming an eyesore after a while. i was actually looking up coasters online to expand my collections and just basically giving myself some variations, but it all changed once i went to this cafe with konco. they had a cool, yellow paper coaster with white lines and design and i got one when they serve me my drinks. due to my lack of better judgements, i yoinked that thing when we left the cafe lmao (legally) (i guess) (kinda....?) (for LEGAL REASONS pls don't replicate this action). but since that day, i become addicted to ~~steal~~ borrow some coasters from various cafes and restaurant that i went to. my friends even participated in this hobby (AGAIN, PLS DON'T DO IT), giving me ~~stolen~~ coasters to be added to the collection for the hell of it. i mean... now i own probably around 30-40 coasters (?), and all of them are cool and have tons of stories behind it.

all and all, yes i do own various coasters. yes all of them are cool. yes some of them can be seen below. no pls don't give me your stolen coasters when we meet irl. and no pls don't do this like frfr JANGAN NYOLONG KARENA LOTSO DID THAT TOO OK TRIMS EVERYONE HV A GOOD DAY
